# Comment & Code Hygiene

## No ticket references in code or comments

Never reference issue-tracker tickets (Linear, Jira, GitHub issues, etc.) in code
or comments. They rot, leak internal context, and mean nothing to a future reader
of the source. Explain the *reasoning* directly instead.

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — opaque ticket reference
// Warm dispatchers early. See SDK-4507.
OneSignalDispatchers.prewarm()

// ✅ GOOD — the reason lives in the comment
// Warm dispatchers off the main thread so the first caller doesn't pay the
// thread-pool + dispatcher construction cost (observed as multi-second main-thread blocks).
OneSignalDispatchers.prewarm()
```

## Keep comments direct and non-redundant

- Cut filler, restated code, and obvious narration (`// increment i`, `// return result`).
- State the *why* (intent, trade-off, constraint), not the *what* the code already shows.
- Prefer one tight sentence over a paragraph; drop hedging and repetition.
- Don't duplicate the same explanation across multiple comments — say it once.

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — narrates the code, redundant
// Loop over each module in the modules list and register it with the builder
for (module in modules) { module.register(this) }

// ✅ GOOD — omit; the code is self-evident
for (module in modules) { module.register(this) }
```

## Checklist before finishing code

- [ ] No ticket IDs referenced in code or comments
- [ ] Comments explain intent/trade-offs, not the obvious
- [ ] No redundant or duplicated comments
